Using Vite
Create a new project:
npm create vite@latest
Move into the project:
cd my-app
Install dependencies:
npm install
Start the development server:
npm run dev


Difference Between npx create-react-app and npm create vite@latest
Interview Answer

npx create-react-app uses Webpack and bundles the entire application before serving it,
making startup and rebuilds slower. npm create vite@latest uses Vite, which leverages native ES Modules during development 
and provides much faster startup, instant Hot Module Replacement, and quicker production builds. For new React applications, 
Vite is generally the preferred choice.

Important Files to Remember

# React App Structure – Important Files

| File | Purpose |
|------|---------|
| `index.html` | Main HTML page containing the `<div id="root"></div>` where the React application is mounted. |
| `main.jsx` | Entry point of the application. It renders the root `App` component into the `root` div. |
| `App.jsx` | Root component of the application where the main UI starts. |
| `index.css` | Global CSS styles applied across the entire application. |
| `App.css` | Styles specific to the `App` component. |
| `assets/` | Stores static assets imported into components, such as images, fonts, SVGs, and videos. |
| `public/` | Stores static files served directly by the browser (e.g., `favicon.ico`, images, PDFs). |
| `package.json` | Contains project metadata, dependencies, scripts, and configuration. |
| `vite.config.js` | Configuration file for Vite, including plugins and development/build settings. |

## React Rendering Flow

```text
index.html
     │
     ▼
<div id="root"></div>
     │
     ▼
main.jsx
     │
     ▼
<App />
     │
     ▼
Child Components
     │
     ▼
Browser UI
```

