Writing Your First React App
Simple Definition
Writing a React app means creating components that return JSX, which React renders as the user interface in the browser.

Step 1: Open App.jsx
A new Vite React project contains an App.jsx file. Replace its contents with your own component.
function App() {
    return (
        <h1>Hello, React!</h1>
    );
}
export default App;

Step 2: Understand the Code
function App() {
    return (
        <h1>Hello, React!</h1>
    );
}

export default App;


Explanation
function App() → Defines a React component.
return → Specifies the UI to display.
<h1>Hello, React!</h1> → JSX returned by the component.
export default App → Makes the component available to other files.



Step 3: Render the App
In main.jsx:
import React from "react";
import ReactDOM from "react-dom/client";
import App from "./App";
ReactDOM.createRoot(document.getElementById("root")).render(
    <App />
);

main.jsx
    │
    ▼
<App />
    │
    ▼
App.jsx
    │
    ▼
<h1>Hello, React!</h1>
    │
    ▼
Browser


Step 4: Return Multiple Elements
Wrap multiple elements inside a single parent.
function App() {
    return (
        <div>
            <h1>Welcome</h1>
            <p>This is my first React app.</p>
        </div>
    );
}
export default App;

Step 5: Use JavaScript Inside JSX
Use curly braces {} to embed JavaScript expressions.
function App() {
    const name = "John";

    return (
        <h1>Hello, {name}!</h1>
    );
}
export default App;


Step 6: Add Simple Styling
function App() {
    return (
        <h1 style={{ color: "blue" }}>
            Hello React
        </h1>
    );
}
export default App;
Note: Inline styles in React use a JavaScript object.


Step 7: Display Dynamic Data
function App() {
    const age = 22;

    return (
        <div>
            <h2>Name: John</h2>
            <h2>Age: {age}</h2>
        </div>
    );
}
export default App;


